fields.name: Wagner Sarmento
fields.message: Olá! Meu nome é Wagner Sarmento, sou um jornalista e historiador brasileiro, trabalho na TV Globo, uma rede de televisão aqui em meu país, e estou escrevendo um livro sobre o legado do diplomata Sergio Vieira de Mello, que trabalhou na ONU e serviu em Timor-Leste. Foi aí uma de suas principais missões, pois ajudou o país em seu processo de independência e também a caminhar com as próprias pernas, após anos de domínio indonésio. Estamos avaliando a possibilidade de viajar até Timor-Leste para conhecer a nação e conhecer um pouco da herança deixada pelo trabalho de Vieira de Mello. Dentro disso, a figura do senhor Xanana Gusmao, por sua importância histórica, é fundamental. Gostaria de uma forma de entrar em contato com ele - via telefone ou e-mail - para lhe contar mais detalhes sobre o projeto, sobre nosso plano de viagem e também - e sobretudo - porque queremos entrevistá-lo para este livro. Agradeço pela atenção e aguardo um retorno. Obrigado.

fields.body_en: Our library at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is open for the public and is home to an extensive collection of books and multimedia materials. Our collections include a wide range of topics and children’s books/activities. Our library catalogue is also available to view online. Customers within the library can access free internet and learn about Timor-Leste and it’s history through our audio-visual selections.
fields.body_tet: Ami nia biblioteka iha Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão loke ba públiku no sai nudar uma ba koleksaun livru wain tebes no material multimedia sira. Ami-nia koleksaun inklui livru/aktividade ho topiku oioin  ba labarik sira. Ami-nia katalogasaun bilioteka mos bele haree online. Kliente sira nebe mak mai iha billioteka bele asesu internet gratuita no aprende konaba Timor-Leste ho ninia istoria liu husi ami-nia selesaun audio-vizual.

fields.body_en: The museum at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room will enable you immerse yourself in Timor-Leste's historical journey to independence and celebrate today's art and culture. Come visit our permanent and temporary rolling exhibitions by local and international artists. There is a diverse array of events and exhibitions happening at the museum on any given day. A fusion of art, music, culture and current affairs. Come visit us.
fields.body_tet: Muzeu iha Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão sei fo biban ba ita-boot atu habesik an liu tan ho jornada istoriku Timor-Leste nian ba independensia no selebra arte no kultura ohin loron nian.  Mai vizita ami-nia espozisaun permanente no temporariu husi artisita lokal no internasional sira. Eventu no espozisaun oin-oin mak akontese iha muzeu iha kulaker loron. Sei iha mos kombinasaun ho arte, muzika, kultura no asuntu aktualizadu. Mai vizita ami.

fields.body_en: Take a look at our permanent exhibitions to learn about the history of Timor-Leste
fields.body_tet: Hare ami nia espozisaun permanente atu aprende konaba istoria Timor-Leste.

fields.body_en: See what we exciting exhibitions we have displayed right now in the museum
fields.body_tet: Haree espozisaun sira furak tebes ne'ebé mak ami hatudu agora iha muzeu.

fields.body_en: Our digital catalogue is home to our collection which includes over 4000 materials. Browse our general collection, audiovisual collection, children's collection and our very important Timor-Leste Reference collection.
fields.body_tet: Ami-nia katalogasaun dijital mak uma ba ami-nia koleksaun sira inklui material sira barak liu 4000. Konsulta ho ami-nia koleksaun jeral,  koleksaun audiovizual, koleksaun ba labarik sira no ami-nia koleksaun importante tebes Referensia Timor-Leste.

fields.body_en: Our library at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is home to an extensive collection of books and multimedia materials. Customers within the library can access free internet and learn about Timor-Leste and it’s history through our audio-visual selections.

Kliente sira iha bibilioteka bele asesu internet gratuita no aprende konaba Timor-Leste no ninia istoria liu husi ami-nia selesaun audio-visual.

This is the second cruise ship visit after the successfuk visit in last year. On 12 of February there was a big tourist visit coming to Dili with more than 800 ppl from Australia. These tourist are visiting different places in Dili such as resitance museum, Dare, Cristo Rei, Largo Lecidere, Santa Cruz cemetery, and Hotel Novo Tourismu to see the cultural performance. Likewise last year, the reading room also included in their tours. The next Cruise Ship will be coming on 8 of March with approximately 1,500 people. As the result of this visit local people who are selling their artcrafts many were sold out in Tais Market as one of the local news reported today.

This is the second cruise ship visit after the successful visit in last year. On 12th of February there was a big tourist visit coming to Dili with more than 800 people from Australia. These tourist are visiting different places in Dili such as the Resistance museum, Dare, Cristo Rei, Largo Lecidere, Santa Cruz cemetery, and Hotel Novo Tourismu to see the cultural performance. Likewise last year, the Reading Room was also included in their tours. The next Cruise Ship will be coming on 8 of March with approximately 1,500 people. The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is a free for the public library, museum and community space in Dili, Timor-Leste. The Reading Room was opened in June of 2000 by founder Kirsty Sword-Gusm\u00e3o with the goal of being a safe, open space for the community to learn and thrive- a goal that continues to be upheld today in everything that we do.

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. The Reading Room was founded in the year 2000 by first lady Kirsty Sword Gusm\u00e3o and has grown since then to the lively, peaceful space that caters to over 2000 visitors per month. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.\u00a0

Our vision:\u00a0Creating the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity.\u00a0

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room (XGRR) is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. The Reading Room was founded in the year 2000 by first lady Kirsty Sword Gusm\u00e3o and has grown since then to the lively, peaceful space that caters to over 2000 visitors per month. Our facilities include free to use computers and internet, an extensive collection of books and visual/audio materials (over 4000), an online catalogue, museum exhibitions, a children's area and various bookable community areas. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.\u00a0

Our vision:\u00a0Creating the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity.\u00a0

Our Vision:\u00a0Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission:\u00a0To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values:\u00a0Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity.\u00a0

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room (XGRR) is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. Our facilities include free to use computers and internet, an extensive collection of books and visual/audio materials (over 4000), an online catalogue, museum exhibitions, a children's area and various bookable community areas. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.

Our library at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is open for the public to use and is home to an extensive collection of books and multimedia materials. {"carousel_items": [{"link_page": null, "embed_url": "", "description": "Snapshots of our free to visit permanent exhibitions that are displayed in our museum", "image": 77, "link_external": "", "caption": "Permanent Exhibitions", "sort_order": 0, "link_document": null, "pk": 3, "button_link": "", "page": 38}], "date_to": null, "search_description": "", "owner": 5, "intro": "", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "time_to": null, "is_permanent": true, "go_live_at": null, "feed_image": 77, "title": "Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Exhibit", "date_from": null, "seo_title": "", "slug": "xanana-gusm\u00e3o-exhibit", "live": true, "location": "", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

Gusm\u00e3o was born in\u00a0Manatuto, in what was then\u00a0Portuguese Timor, to parents of mixed Portuguese-Timorese ancestry, both of whom were school teachers.[2]\u00a0He attended a\u00a0Jesuit\u00a0high school just outside\u00a0Dili. After leaving high-school for financial reasons at the age of fifteen, he held a variety of unskilled jobs, while continuing his education at night school. In 1965, at the age of 19, he met Emilia Batista, who was later to become his wife. His nickname, \"Xanana\", was taken from the name of the American rock and roll band\u00a0Sha Na Na, who in turn were named after a lyric from a doo-wop song of 1957 by\u00a0the Silhouettes.

In 1966, Gusm\u00e3o obtained a position with the public service, which allowed him to continue his education. This was interrupted in 1968 when Gusm\u00e3o was recruited by the\u00a0Portuguese Army\u00a0for national service. He served for three years, rising to the rank of corporal. During this time, he married Emilia Batista, with whom he had a son Eugenio, and a daughter Zenilda. He has since divorced Emilia, and in 2000, he married Australian\u00a0Kirsty Sword, with whom he had three sons: Alexandre, Kay Olok and Daniel. In 1971, Gusm\u00e3o completed his national service, his son was born, and he became involved with a nationalist organisation headed by\u00a0Jos\u00e9 Ramos-Horta. For the next three years he was actively involved in peaceful protests directed at the colonial system.

It was in 1974 that a\u00a0coup in Portugal\u00a0resulted in the beginning of decolonisation for Portuguese Timor, and shortly afterwards the Governor\u00a0M\u00e1rio Lemos Pires\u00a0announced plans to grant the colony independence. Plans were drawn up to hold general elections with a view to independence in 1978. During most of 1975 a bitter internal struggle occurred between two rival factions in Portuguese Timor. Gusm\u00e3o became deeply involved with the\u00a0FRETILIN\u00a0faction, and as a result he was arrested and imprisoned by the rival faction the Timorese Democratic Union (UDT) in mid-1975. Taking advantage of the internal disorder, and with an eye to absorbing the colony,\u00a0Indonesia\u00a0immediately began a campaign of destabilisation, and frequent raids into Portuguese Timor were staged from Indonesian\u00a0West Timor. By late 1975 the Fretilin faction had gained control of Portuguese Timor and Gusm\u00e3o was released from prison. He was given the position of Press Secretary within the FRETILIN organisation. On 28 November 1975, Fretilin declared the independence of Portuguese Timor as \"The Democratic Republic of East Timor\", and Gusm\u00e3o was responsible for filming the ceremony. Nine days later,\u00a0Indonesia invaded East Timor. At the time Gusm\u00e3o was visiting friends outside of Dili and he witnessed the invasion from the hills. For the next few days he searched for his family.

Come visit the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room to find out more.

Our Mission, Vision and Values


Our Vision:\u00a0Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission:\u00a0To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values:\u00a0Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity.\u00a0

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room (XGRR) is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. Our facilities include free to use computers and internet, an extensive collection of books and visual/audio materials (over 4000), an online catalogue, museum exhibitions, a children's area and various bookable community areas. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.

Board of Governors

Staff Directory

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-18T02:46:31.136Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "About", "seo_title": "About", "slug": "about", "live": true, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "body": "

Our Mission, Vision and Values


Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room


The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.

Board of Governors 


It is the Boards' responsibility to ensure that the Coordinator is doing his job well and that the XGRR is not at risk. Regular board meetings are held, board members participate in events and fundraising. The board members are as follows:

Patron/Chair: Kirsty Sword Gusmao

Deputy of Chair: Joào Martires

Members:

  • Sebastian da Silva
  • Mara Bernades de Sa
  • Francisca Maia
  • Palmira Pires
  • Maria Isabel de Jesus Ximenes
  • Jenny Coles
  • Sandi Paul
  • Bernabe (Abe) Barreto
Advisers
  • Del Bovill
  • Anya Dettman. National Library of Australia
  • Ina Fautua. New Zealand Embassy, Papua New Guinea     
  • Patti Manolis. CEO Geelong Libraries, Australia 

Staff Directory


Our staff is dedicated, wonderful and will be helpful when you visit the Reading Room. We love visitors. We look forward to hosting you. Our team members are as follows:

Permanent Staff:

  • Gaspar Freitas, Manager
  • Domingos Pereira, Team Leader – Library and Museum
  • Maria Amaral Guteeres, Scholarship Program Administrator
  • Arsenio da Costa, Digital Library Assistant
  • Felizarda Tilman, Finance and HR Assistant
Temporary Volunteers:

National

  • Jose Paul
  • Inacio
  • ….. 

International

  • Sam Knowles (UniVol – VSA)

", "latest_revision_created_at": null, "go_live_at": null, "title": "Support", "seo_title": "Support Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room", "slug": "support", "live": true, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

The Reading Room relies upon kind donations from the national and international community in order to continue to carry out it's vital work with literacy and resource accessibility in Timor-Leste. Your donations help us to stock and run the library, with exhibitions for the public, and assist us to hold important trainings/community events. The XGRR and its users are extremely thankful to our donors. You can donate today to the XGRR in various ways:\u00a0


Bank Donations


Through our Timor-Leste bank account:\u00a0

(BANK ACCT #)\u00a0


Book Donations


Please ensure that items and/or books are in good condition and relevant to the Reading Room. Please drop off your donations to us at Lobo No. 1, Rua Belarmino, Bidau Lecidere, Dili


Time/Skills


The Reading Room is a popular public spot and we are always looking for those in the Dili community who would be interested in holding any trainings or events in our spaces. If you have a skill set that you think the community could benefit from and you are interested in committing some time in passing some skills on, please e-mail us at: xgreadingroom@gmail.com OR come in and talk to us at: Lobo No. 1, Rua Belarmino, Bidau Lecidere, Dili.



If you do donate, please don't hesitate to e-mail us at xgreadingroom@gmail.com to get in touch so that we can reply with our gratitude!\u00a0

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

Transport

http://www.ramelau.com/business-directory/transport.html

On the 21st of June 2017 the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room celebrated their 17th anniversary. The Xanana Gusmao Reading Room has been going for 17 years with the aim of creating the next generation of readers in Timor-Leste. On this day we had a book sale to help encourage everyone to read! Many members of the public came along and books were sold for as little as 10c! The funds from the book sale will go towards improving the\\u00a0Xanana Gusmao Reading Room even more.

The staff celebrated their accomplishments over the years after work with cake and Timorense coffee whilst talking about how far the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room has come! They had discussions about their progress and goals they want to accomplish in the future.

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room has a new exhibition opening on Wednesday 16th August at 1:30 pm, I welcome you to come along and please do pass on this message to friends and colleagues or anyone who might be interested.\u00a0


Entry FREE!


This exhibition at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is in memory of the events which took place in 1999 which opened the path to the restoration of independence for Timor-Leste!\u00a0The main feature of this exhibition is a collection of memories from ordinary people. We asked the Timorese public to bring in a piece of their history from 1999. These stories represent different experiences from the Timorese at that time.


For this exhibition, we are also collaborating with Centro Nacional Chega (CNC) to help our visitors have a better understanding about the history leading up to the vote for independence.

This exhibition will run from the 16th August until the 4th September, Monday- Saturday 9am - 5pm


Opening Day Program:

1:30, Registration

1:45, Welcome introduction and singing of national anthem

2:00, Offical opening of exhibition by S.E. Dra. Maria Isabel de Jesus Ximenes, Securtery of Art and Culture

2:15, Veterans Talkshow

5:30, Coffee and finishing remarks


There will also be;

Songs sung from the resistance times on the 17th, 24th and 31st August in the afternoon\u00a0

Activities for children 19th and 27th August, 2nd September in the morning.

For the end of our latest exhibition \u201cMemory \u201899\u201d the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room are holding an event on the exhibition\u2019s last day, Monday 4th September.


This exhibition at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is in memory of the events that took place in 1999 which opened the path to the restoration of independence for Timor-Leste!


The main feature of this exhibition is a collection of memories from ordinary people. We asked the Timorese public to bring in a piece of their history from 1999. These stories represent different experiences from the Timorese at that time.\u00a0This event will include some activities in the day time such as youth discussions with guest speakers from CNC and Centro Audiovisual Max Stahl Timor-Leste at 10 am and then from 3 pm activities for children and youth.


On the evening of the 4th there will be a premiere of Centro Audiovisual Max Stahl Timor-Leste\u2019s new documentary movie called \"Reconciliation, Part One\", along with some guest speakers and food to share. Registration will begin at 5:30, introduction/welcome speeches from 5:45 and then the movie will start at 6:30 running for 1 hour. The evening will finish with comments from the audience and some food to share.


Come along to this event and bring your friends and family!

{"carousel_items": [{"link_page": null, "embed_url": "", "description": "", "image": 102, "link_external": "", "caption": "'99 Memories", "sort_order": 0, "link_document": null, "pk": 1, "button_link": "", "page": 21}], "search_description": "News at the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room", "owner": 2, "intro": "

The XGRR currently have an exhibition happening \"Memory '99\". This exhibition at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is in memory of the events which took place in 1999 which opened the path to the restoration of independence for Timor-Leste!

The main feature of this exhibition is a collection of memories from ordinary people. We asked the Timorese public to bring in a piece of their history from 1999. These stories represent different experiences from the Timorese at that time.

Last Saturday Chega! comics were read to children to help teach them about the history of the resistance times

Today a group of Timorese youth sat around and sung popular songs from the resistance times

Come along tomorrow, 24th August at 3pm to sing songs from the resistance times or bring your children along on the 26th August at 10 am to hear some stories.

These events are on going until the 4th of September. These events are kindly supported by the New Zealand Embassy of Timor-Leste.

Do not miss out this opportunity!

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-05-24T03:45:48.741Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "About", "seo_title": "About", "slug": "about", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2017-05-24T03:45:48.741Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

Our Mission, Vision and Values


Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room


The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.

Board of Governors 


It is the Boards' responsibility to ensure that the Coordinator is doing his job well and that the XGRR is not at risk. Regular board meetings are held, board members participate in events and fundraising. The board members are as follows:

Patron/Chair: Kirsty Sword Gusmao

Deputy of Chair: Joào Martires

Members:

  • Sebastian da Silva
  • Mara Bernades de Sa
  • Francisca Maia
  • Palmira Pires
  • Maria Isabel de Jesus Ximenes
  • Jenny Coles
  • Sandi Paul
  • Bernabe (Abe) Barreto
Advisers:

  • Del Bovill
  • Anya Dettman. National Library of Australia
  • Ina Fautua. New Zealand Embassy, Papua New Guinea     
  • Patti Manolis. CEO Geelong Libraries, Australia 

Staff Directory


Our staff is dedicated, wonderful and will be helpful when you visit the Reading Room. We love visitors. We look forward to hosting you. Our team members are as follows:

Permanent Staff:

  • Gaspar Freitas, Manager
  • Domingos Pereira, Team Leader – Library and Museum
  • Maria Amaral Guteeres, Scholarship Program Administrator
  • Arsenio da Costa, Digital Library Assistant
  • Felizarda Tilman, Finance and HR Assistant
Temporary Volunteers:

National

  • Jose Paulo Jeronimo
  • Inacio de Loiola Soares
  • Etelvina da Silva
  • Jeronimo Fernandez

International

  • Sam Knowles (UniVol – VSA)

Today at the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room, we started leadership training from Movimentu Tane Timor and Lorico Dili Redline teams, for young people, students, and the community. This training will be held for a week from 9 am to 10 am and will continue in the afternoon from 2 pm to 3 pm. For anyone who want to join in this training, please come to Xanana Gusmao Reading Room, in Uma Mahon.

You can see the topics that will be taken for a week, below:


October, 9: Basic Communication and Leadership Introduction

October, 10 : Community Leadership and Server Leadership.

October, 11 : Ethics Leadership and Leadership Speak in\u00a0Public.

October, 12 : Leadership Management and Leadership in\u00a0Organisation.

October, 13 : Conflict Resolution and Humanitarian\u00a0Leadership.

October, 14 : Youth Role and Women in Leadership.

The Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is a free for the public library, museum and community space in Dili, Timor-Leste. The Reading Room was opened in June of 2000 by founder Kirsty Sword-Gusm\u00e3o with the goal of being a safe, open space for the community to learn and thrive- a goal that continues to be upheld today in everything that we do.

Ami nia biblioteka iha Sala Leitura\u00a0Xanana Gusm\u00e3o\u00a0loke ba publiku no sai nudar uma ba koleksaun livru no material multimedia barak tebes. ", "body_en": "

Our library at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room is open for the public and is home to an extensive collection of books and multimedia materials. The museum at the Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room will enable you immerse yourself in Timor-Leste's historical journey to independence and celebrate today's art and culture. A fusion of art, music, culture and current affairs. Come visit us.

{"carousel_items": [{"description_tet": "Aprende barak tan konaba Xanana Gusmão Reading Room", "button_link_en": "", "link_page": null, "embed_url": "", "image": 51, "link_external": "", "description_en": "Learn more about the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room", "caption_en": "About Us", "sort_order": 0, "link_document": null, "pk": 1, "button_link_tet": "", "caption_tet": "Konaba Ami", "page": 4}], "search_description": "", "owner": 2, "intro": "

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. Our facilities include free to use computers and internet, an extensive collection of books and visual/audio materials (over 4000), an online catalogue, museum exhibitions, a children's area and various bookable community areas. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.

Our Mission, Vision and Values

Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.

Board of Governors 

It is the Boards' responsibility to ensure that the Coordinator is doing his job well and that the XGRR is not at risk. Regular board meetings are held, board members participate in events and fundraising. The board members are as follows:

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-02T03:43:05.082Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Tourist Information", "seo_title": "", "slug": "tourist-information", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2017-06-02T03:43:05.082Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-17T08:55:09.398Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Support", "seo_title": "Support Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room", "slug": "support", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-17T08:55:09.486Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

The Reading Room relies upon kind donations from the national and international community in order to continue to carry out it's vital work with literacy and resource accessibility in Timor-Leste. Your donations help us to stock and run the library, with exhibitions for the public, and assist us to hold important trainings/community events. The XGRR and its users are extremely thankful to our donors. You can donate today to the XGRR in various ways:\u00a0


Bank Donations


Through our Timor-Leste bank account:\u00a0

BANK ACCT #\u00a0105559

IBAN:\u00a0TL38 0030 0000 0001 0555 937


Book Donations


Please ensure that items and/or books are in good condition and relevant to the Reading Room. Please drop off your donations to us at Lobo No. 1, Rua Belarmino, Bidau Lecidere, Dili


Time/Skills


The Reading Room is a popular public spot and we are always looking for those in the Dili community who would be interested in holding any trainings or events in our spaces. If you have a skill set that you think the community could benefit from and you are interested in committing some time in passing some skills on, please e-mail us at: xgreadingroom@gmail.com OR come in and talk to us at: Lobo No. 1, Rua Belarmino, Bidau Lecidere, Dili.



If you do donate, please don't hesitate to e-mail us at xgreadingroom@gmail.com to get in touch so that we can reply with our gratitude!\u00a0

{"carousel_items": [{"description_tet": "Informasaun balun mak sei ajuda tebes vizitante sira mai iha Timor-Leste", "button_link_en": "", "link_page": null, "embed_url": "", "image": 70, "link_external": "", "description_en": "A bit of information that will be useful for visitors to Timor Leste", "caption_en": "Tourist Information", "sort_order": 0, "link_document": null, "pk": 3, "button_link_tet": "", "caption_tet": "Informasaun Turista", "page": 43}], "search_description": "", "owner": 5, "intro": "

Here you will find a bit of information about what to know, where to go, things to see, as well as how to go about your visit in the beautiful country of Timor Leste.

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-17T08:54:12.228Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Tourist Information", "seo_title": "", "slug": "tourist-information", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-17T08:54:12.313Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

Useful Websites

General Timor-Leste information


http://visiteasttimor.com/

http://www.timorleste.tl/

https://www.lonelyplanet.com/east-timor

http://www.ramelau.com/index.html\u00a0


Atauro


http://www.barrys-place-atauro.com/

http://ataurotourism.org/

http://www.beloibeachhoteltimorleste.com/


Transport


https://www.easttimor-timorleste.com/Vehicle_Car_Boat_Rentals_East_Timor_Leste_Dili.htm

http://www.ramelau.com/business-directory/transport.html

http://www.rentlocarhire.com,\u00a0Mobile: +(670) 7741 6983

Taltabi Motor Rentals:\u00a0Tel (+670) 7795 7364/7723 4777

Here you will find a bit of information about what to know, where to go, things to see, as well as how to go about your visit in the beautiful country of Timor Leste.

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-18T02:57:52.394Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Tourist Information", "seo_title": "", "slug": "tourist-information", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-18T02:57:52.501Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

Here you will find a bit of information about what to know, where to go, things to see, as well as how to go about your visit in the beautiful country of Timor Leste.

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-18T03:46:34.510Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Tourist Information", "seo_title": "", "slug": "tourist-information", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-18T03:46:34.584Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-17T08:09:43.687Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "About", "seo_title": "About", "slug": "about", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-17T08:09:43.758Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

Our Mission, Vision and Values

Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.

Board of Governors 

It is the Boards' responsibility to ensure that the Coordinator is doing his job well and that the XGRR is not at risk. Regular board meetings are held, board members participate in events and fundraising. The board members are as follows:

Staff Directory

Our staff is dedicated, wonderful and will be helpful when you visit the Reading Room. We love visitors. We look forward to hosting you. Our team members are as follows:

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-18T05:54:36.235Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Tourist Information", "seo_title": "", "slug": "tourist-information", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-18T05:54:36.329Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

General Information

Currency: $USD, US notes and Timorese coins are used


Visa: When you arrive at the airport, the custom officers will issue a single-entry visa valid for 30 days and you must show a valid return ticket, proof of sufficient funds and your accommodation booking. You will also need to fill out immigration, as well as Customs forms


Climate: East Timor has two seasons. The wet season is December to April and the dry season is May to November. Daytime temperatures in the lowland area ranges from 30\u00b0C to 35\u00b0C dropping into the low 20\u2019s overnight. In the mountains temperatures can drop as low as 15\u00b0C overnight.


Language: Tetum and Portuguese are the official languages. English and Indonesian are also widely spoken throughout Timor-Leste.


Religion: Approximately 95% of East Timorese are Catholic. Religious days are closely observed, loud noise and frivolous behaviour are frowned on during these times.


Water: Water used for drinking, brushing teeth or making ice should be boiled or sterilised. It is recommended to drink bottled water. In the tropics it is important to drink plenty of non-alcoholic fluids to avoid dehydration.


Shopping: In the centre of Dili, the local market is a great spot to meet the locals and find batiks and embroidered fabrics in traditional patterns and colours along with coral jewellery and woodcarvings. The coffee from Timor-Leste is unique and different from other coffees around the world. It is organically grown, renowned for its sharp flavour and definitely worth a try.


Diving: Timor-Leste offers the adventurous diver the opportunity to explore the unexplored and has some of the most accessible shore diving in South East Asia. Alternatively you can venture out to the famous Atauro Island, a 45 minute boat ride from Dili. Average water temperature is 28\u00b0C. A protective lycra suit or \u00a03mm suit is recommended. Best visibility is between July to October.\u00a0


Departure Tax: A local tax of US$10 is to be on departure at the airport. Please have US cash available.


Ways to get around:

  • Microlet 25c
  • Taxi (yellow) $2-5
  • Taxi (blue) $3-7
  • Motorbike/ scooter- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Car- can be hired short term or bought for long term
  • Bus- for travel from district to district

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) is a non-governmental organisation that consists of a library, museum and general community space (all free to visit) in the heart of Dili. Our facilities include free to use computers and internet, an extensive collection of books and visual/audio materials (over 4000), an online catalogue, museum exhibitions, a children's area and various bookable community areas. We keep our vision, mission and values central to everything that we do.

", "latest_revision_created_at": "2018-04-18T06:02:23.244Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "About", "seo_title": "About", "slug": "about", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2018-04-18T06:02:23.365Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "

Our Mission, Vision and Values

Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.

Board of Governors 

It is the Boards' responsibility to ensure that the Coordinator is doing his job well and that the XGRR is not at risk. Regular board meetings are held, board members participate in events and fundraising. The board members are as follows:

Staff Directory

fields.location: Uma Mahon - Xanana Gusmao Reading Room
fields.body_en: We shall hold a workshop for children and parents at the Reading Room. The workshop is designed to engage parents and children to learn together with various educational activities. Some activities such as playing games, puzzles and drawing. The reading hoped that by having this workshop parents can be aware of many educational opportunities that the reading room provided. They will be more engaged with the reading room to use our resources with their children. The workshop will be conducted once a week every Thursday and will last for 45 minutes.

Come and enjoy with your children with this event, you can find various story about child explorers such us  Aiknanoik, Timor Leste History, Xanana's history, etc. And there are has many games for children to develop more their mind. This events will be in the Bebeteka space, so come and join with your children. Viva Labarik Timor Leste !!!

This is the second cruise ship visit after the successful visit in last year. On 12th of February there was a big tourist visit coming to Dili with more than 800 people from Australia. These tourist are visiting different places in Dili such as the Resistance museum, Dare, Cristo Rei, Largo Lecidere, Santa Cruz cemetery, and Hotel Novo Tourismu to see the cultural performance. Likewise last year, the Reading Room was also included in their tours. The next Cruise Ship will be coming on 8 of March with approximately 1,500 people. As the result of this visit local people who are selling their artcrafts many were sold out in Tais Market as one of the local news reported today.

To remember those involved in the 1999 Timor-Leste referendum day the  Xanana Gusmao Reading Room will be holding an exhibition. We invite anyone who has a personal story from this time to come and share. From the 1st until the 31st of August we are going to hold an exhibition in the museum to share everyday people's stories. This exhibition has a focus on how everyday people were effected, not just the hero's that many people hear about more commonly.

If you have something to share with everyone please come along to the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room and fill out the '99 memories form. We are wanting a piece of something for example news paper clipping, photos, clothing or documents. If you can bring this in to share we will take a photo or scan the document to display in the exhibition. You can bring these items in from now, until the 30th of July.


Download this form and bring it along with your piece of history!

fields.location: Uma Mahon, Xanana Gusmao Reading Room
fields.body_en:
The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room has a new exhibition opening on Wednesday 16th August at 1:30 pm, I welcome you to come along and please do pass on this message to friends and colleagues or anyone who might be interested. 


Entry FREE!


This exhibition at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is in memory of the events which took place in 1999 which opened the path to the restoration of independence for Timor-Leste! The main feature of this exhibition is a collection of memories from ordinary people. We asked the Timorese public to bring in a piece of their history from 1999. These stories represent different experiences from the Timorese at that time.


For this exhibition, we are also collaborating with Centro Nacional Chega (CNC) to help our visitors have a better understanding about the history leading up to the vote for independence.

This exhibition will run from the 16th August until the 4th September, Monday- Saturday 9am - 5pm


Opening Day Program:

1:30, Registration

1:45, Welcome introduction and singing of national anthem

2:00, Offical opening of exhibition by S.E. Dra. Maria Isabel de Jesus Ximenes, Securtery of Art and Culture

2:15, Veterans Talkshow

5:30, Coffee and finishing remarks


There will also be;

Songs sung from the resistance times on the 17th, 24th and 31st August in the afternoon 

Activities for children 19th and 27th August, 2nd September in the morning.

fields.location: Uma Mahon at Xanana Gusmão Reading Room
fields.body_en:
For the end of our latest exhibition “Memory ‘99” the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room are holding an event on the exhibition’s last day, Monday 4th September.


This exhibition at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is in memory of the events that took place in 1999 which opened the path to the restoration of independence for Timor-Leste!


The main feature of this exhibition is a collection of memories from ordinary people. We asked the Timorese public to bring in a piece of their history from 1999. These stories represent different experiences from the Timorese at that time. This event will include some activities in the day time such as youth discussions with guest speakers from CNC and Centro Audiovisual Max Stahl Timor-Leste at 10 am and then from 3 pm activities for children and youth.


On the evening of the 4th there will be a premiere of Centro Audiovisual Max Stahl Timor-Leste’s new documentary movie called "Reconciliation, Part One", along with some guest speakers and food to share. Registration will begin at 5:30, introduction/welcome speeches from 5:45 and then the movie will start at 6:30 running for 1 hour. The evening will finish with comments from the audience and some food to share.


Come along to this event and bring your friends and family!

fields.location: Uma Mahon at Xanana Gusmão Reading Room
fields.body_en:
Today at the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room, we started leadership training from Movimentu Tane Timor and Lorico Dili Redline teams, for young people, students, and the community. This training will be held for a week from 9 am to 10 am and will continue in the afternoon from 2 pm to 3 pm. For anyone who want to join in this training, please come to Xanana Gusmao Reading Room, in Uma Mahon.

You can see the topics that will be taken for a week, below:


October, 9: Basic Communication and Leadership Introduction

October, 10 : Community Leadership and Server Leadership.

October, 11 : Ethics Leadership and Leadership Speak in Public.

October, 12 : Leadership Management and Leadership in Organisation.

October, 13 : Conflict Resolution and Humanitarian Leadership.

October, 14 : Youth Role and Women in Leadership.

fields.location: Uma Mahon, Museum and Book Shop at Xanana Gusmão Reading Room
fields.body_en:
Join us for the official opening of ‘Oxfam and Timor-Leste: Our Story’ exhibition, bringing you unique and moving accounts from Oxfam’s 42 years of solidarity, support and partnership with the people of Timor-Leste. Be inspired by untold stories, rare photographs and archival material


‘Our Story’ will be open for free public viewing until Saturday 9 December.

fields.location: Uma Mahon Lea-Ziaval at Xanana Gusmão Reading Room
fields.body_en:
Join us in commemorating National Hero's Day on the 7th of December 2017.


There will be a public discussion with special guest speaker Coronel Falur Rate laek; Chefe Estado Maior F-FDTL. The topic of the discussion is; “Reflesaun Ba Aswain Sira Nian Hodi Luta Hasoru Invazor Sira” 

Reflection of heros fighting in the invasion.....


and launching of Max Stahl film with the title; “Dala Ruma Ha’u Tenki Koalia Maka’as” ("Sometimes I Must Talk Loud")

fields.location: Uma Mahon at Xanana Gusmão Reading Room
fields.body_en:
'Hadomi Rai' is a collection of Timorese students’ portraits and stories about ‘ordinary’ people working in traditional markets. The photos were selected by our subjects for local exhibitions. It is how they want others to 'hare’e no hatene ami', to see and understand us.


Free event. Guests welcome.


'The beauty of our landscape is well-known. My hope is that this book will help readers appreciate the beauty of our people.' 

His Excellency Dr José Ramos-Horta.

fields.tease_en: Our library at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is open for the public to use and is home to an extensive collection of books and multimedia materials. Our collections include general lending materials on a wide range of topics and children’s books/activities. Our library catalogue is also available to view online. Customers within the library can access free internet and learn about Timor-Leste and it’s history through our audio-visual selections.

[{"type": "intro", "value": "

fields.tease_en: Remembering the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room Anniversary
fields.body_en:
[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "

On the 21st of June 2017 the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room celebrated their 17th anniversary. The Xanana Gusmao Reading Room has been going for 17 years with the aim of creating the next generation of readers in Timor-Leste. On this day we had a book sale to help encourage everyone to read! Many members of the public came along and books were sold for as little as 10c! The funds from the book sale will go towards improving the\u00a0Xanana Gusmao Reading Room even more.

The staff celebrated their accomplishments over the years after work with cake and Timorense coffee whilst talking about how far the Xanana Gusmao Reading Room has come! They had discussions about their progress and goals they want to accomplish in the future.

", "id": "f7f8a68e-16f8-4455-9e3f-d49fa2e2873c"}]

fields.tease_en: Sharing lunch with students from the English Conversation Classes
fields.body_en:
[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Recently at Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room we held a lunch for the english class. At this lunch we farewelled mana Sandra and welcomed some new teachers, maun Adrian and mana Bendita.\u00a0Sandra has helped with the english classes at XGRR for a long time. She will be missed! Around 30 staff and students enjoyed lunch together whilst talking with one another.\u00a0


English Classes are held in the Uma Mahon at the\u00a0Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room\u00a0every Tuesday and Thursday at 1pm for intermediate classes and 2pm for basic classes. These classes run for 1 hour each, they are run by Australian and New Zealand volunteers and are FREE!\u00a0

", "id": "eb4ab400-33ec-4e30-9682-13922049eaf5"}]

[{"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 112, "caption": "

Take picture together between Australia Study Tour and the student who receive the scholarship

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "be7afa47-eb9f-4fc7-ba32-263bcc539060"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

XGRR is a place for young people, children, and adults to access books and the internet, which is open for the public and all students. And XGRR is also a non-profit organization, in XGRR there is also a scholarship program that gives scholarships to young people who are committed to school but can not afford to pay for school, funds for this program come mostly from foreign donors who care about the education of these young people.

Now, there is a visit from a study tour group from Australia led by Mrs. Kirsty Sword Gusmão and Mrs. Nandy Gurr. This visit was an opportunity to raise funds for a scholarship program established by Mrs. Kirsty Sword Gusmão when becoming Goodwill Ambassador for Education.

Before the visitors visit every room in Xanana Reading Room, as usually XGRR teams  bring tais to 8 visitors including Mrs. Kirsty and Mrs. Nandy, and Le-Ziaval group also received visitors with traditional Timorese dances. After that, the study tour group visit every room in XGRR which is guided by Mr. Gaspar (XGRR Manager) and also Mrs. Kirsty.


", "id": "ee6d30f9-f728-471f-ac6f-7e179abdfa58"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 113, "caption": "

XGRR staff give tais to all member of Australia study tour group

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "5b7ca058-03e9-45eb-99a8-3577aafe1b1d"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 116, "caption": "

Traditional dance from Le-Ziaval

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "e880093d-8960-46ec-91a4-57ee6aa2b76e"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

On this occasion also received participation from 10 students who have been receipt a scholarship from Xanana Reading Room, the study tour group are very happy to be able to discuss with them to know their future plans, their needs, and the challenges they face. And the studentes  do not forget to thank Mrs. Kirsty and her study tour group have been helping their school fees, and they sing Rai Dili Rai Cidade and O rai Timor Furak as a form of their affection to the visitors.


", "id": "1e6401ea-1544-44dc-81ca-7936c82f092d"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 114, "caption": "

Australia study group discussion at uma mahon

", "alignment": "left"}, "id": "1bf01a5f-8d41-4cc0-bf3e-eeed775d8a91"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 115, "caption": "

The scholarship sing for the Australia study tour group 

", "alignment": "right"}, "id": "7b4a32db-912d-4812-a04f-32d328971743"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

The end of this visit the students  and the group do a photo together, Thanks to all of you at Xanana Reading Room, hoping that this visit will give you strength to help XGRR and the students  to help develop education in Timor Leste.

", "id": "296f3bd1-3a8e-429b-8b8c-bd83cecc3572"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 112, "caption": "

Photo group between Australia study tour group and the students

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "68721f24-afc2-4ce7-97dc-f4b6f68ce75b"}]
fields.body_tet:
[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Xanana Reading Room hanesan fatin ba jovem, labrik, no adultu sira hodi asesu ba le’e livru no asesu internet, ne’ebe mak loke gratuita ba komunidade no estudante sira hotu. I XGRR mos hanesan organizasaun ne’ebe mak não lukru,  ne’ebe mos oferese bolso estudo ba jovem sira ne’ebe mak iha komitmentu atu eskola maibe la iha kbi’it, ne’ebe mak nia fundus mai husi doador sira ne’ebe mak maioria husi rai liur ne’ebe mak iha intrese ba desenvolvimentu edukasaun iha Timor Leste.

Dadaun ne’e iha vizita ida husi grupu Study tour husi Australia ne’ebe mak lidera husi Sra. Kirsty Sword Gusmão  no Sra. Nandy Gurr. Vizita ida ne’e nudar oportunidade atu halo angariasaun ba programa bolso estudu ne’ebe mak Sra. Kirsty hari wainhira nia asumi knaar nudar Embaixadora de Boa-Vontade Sobre os Assuntus Educasaun.


", "id": "17dfa802-1b98-4f97-bbc3-9c2132654369"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 98, "caption": "

Foto grupu entre grupu Australia study tour no grupu Le-Ziaval

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "90383507-d253-4338-856e-e3d4730d9087"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Molok vizitante sira tama iha espasu sira iha XGRR, hanesan ita nia kustume bain-bain, wainhira simu bainaka,  ekipa  Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão la haluha tara tais ba vizitante nain 8 inklui Sra. Kirsty no mos Sra. Nandy, no grupu Le-Ziaval mos simu vizitante sira ho dansa kultura Timor nian. Depois de ida ne’e, vizitante sira halao vizita ba kada espasu  idak-idak ne’ebe mak guia husi Sr. Gaspar ( Manager XGRR) no mos Sra. Kirsty.


", "id": "97ace13c-8d3f-4ed9-a658-168628b9f195"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 113, "caption": "

Tara tais ba grupu Australia study tour husi XGRR

", "alignment": "left"}, "id": "874dc8ed-53d5-4af5-8b63-ff3a1ef76b7a"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 116, "caption": "

Dansa tradisional husi grupu Le-Ziaval

", "alignment": "right"}, "id": "a1e7779a-0326-4c99-a1bc-3fb44a9eb215"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 117, "caption": "

Esplikasaun husi Sra. kirsty kona ba espasu sira iha XGRR

", "alignment": "left"}, "id": "263b7f1a-738b-4755-8c7d-be510d311793"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Iha okaziaun ida ne’e hetan partisipasaun mos husi bolseiru nain 10 ne’ebe mak durante ne’e hetan bolso husi Xanana Reading Room, vizitante sira kontente tebes hasoru bolseiru hirak ne’e, tamba sira bele halo diskusaun  ho bolseiru sira hodi hatene sira nia hanoin ba futuru, nesesidade no mos difikuldade ne’ebe mak bolseiru hirak ne’e infrenta. I bolseiru sira mos la haluha hato’o sira nia agradesementu ba Sra. Kirsty no mos ninia kolega sira tamba bele ajuda ona bolseiru sira, I sira mos anima vizitante sira ho musica Rai Dili Rai Cidade no O Rai Timor Furak.


", "id": "95761354-b3a9-452c-a648-e680836b8735"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 115, "caption": "

Bolseiru sira hananu musika Rai Dili Rai Cidande no O rai Timor furak 

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "36b31d6b-ee6f-4b1f-849d-3acb468936b0"}, {"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Rohan ba vizita ida ne’e mak bolseiru sira hasai fotografia hamutuk ho vizitante sira, obrigada barak ba imi nain 8 nia prezensa iha sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão, hein katak ho imi nia vizita ne’e bele fo coragem ba imi atu bele ajuda Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão no mos bolseiru sira hodi hadi dezenvolvimentu edukasaun iha Timor Leste.

", "id": "f3bbaad3-ca05-45b1-be99-6658592ae843"}, {"type": "aligned_image", "value": {"image": 112, "caption": "

Foto hamutuk entre bolseiru XGRR no grupu Australia study tour

", "alignment": "mid"}, "id": "7bc7ac9e-06cf-4834-8627-0e0ed34cc8c1"}]

fields.tease_en: New Zealand Journalist Visit at Xanana Reading Room

fields.body_en:
[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Today in Xanana Gusm\u00e3o Reading Room received a visit from a journalist from New Zealand. On this occasion the journalist didn't forget to visit every space in Xanana Gusmao Reading Room. The most important thing in her visit was that she wanted to have discussions with young people in Timor Leste and also wanted to interview them about the development process of Timor-Leste, the challenges, and the success that they want to achieve. The discussion gained much participation from young people, and they all expressed their concerns and challenges. Examples are the lack of employment in Timor Leste. And they appealed to the government to open jobs in order to reduce unemployment. And they also say that when they finish school they do not get a job, so every day they come to the Xanana Reading Room so they can get information through accessing the internet and reading the newspapers provided at Xanana Reading Room. For that, they are very happy because Reading Room can facilitate them to obtain information in Timor Leste.

[{"type": "paragraph", "value": "

Ohin sala leitura Xanana Gusm\u00e3o\u00a0 simu vizita ida husi jornalista Nova Zelandia nian. Iha oportunidade ne\u2019e jornalista refere la haluha halo ninia vizita ba espasu sira iha sala leitura. Buat ne\u2019ebe mak importante iha vizita ne\u2019e mak jornalista ne\u2019e hakarak dada lia ho jovem Timor oan sira hodi dada lia no intervista jovem sira kona ba jovem sira nia hanoin ba dezenvolvimentu Timor Leste nian, dezafiu sira ne\u2019ebe mak jovem sira infrenta, no mos jovem sira nia susesu iha futuru. Iha diskusaun ne\u2019e hetan partisipasaun barak husi jovem sira, I sira idak-idak hato\u2019o sira nia prekupasaun no mos sira nia dezafiu. Por exemplo kona kampu de trabalho ne\u2019ebe mak minimu liu iha Timor Leste. I jovem sira ne\u2019e ezizi\u00a0 ba governu atu loke tan kampu de trabalho hodi nune\u2019e bele hamenus numeru desemprego. I Jovem sira ne\u2019e mos hatete katak, bainhira sira ramata eskola sira la hetan servisu no loron sira mai vizita\u00a0 Sala Leitura Xanana Gusm\u00e3o hodi nune\u2019e bele hetan informasaun ruma liu husi asesu internet no le\u2019e jornal sira ne\u2019ebe mak prepara ona iha Sala Leitura. Ho nune\u2019e sira kontente tebes tamba Sala Leitura bele ajuda ona sira hodi hafasil sira hetan informasaun ruma iha Timor Leste.

fields.intro_en: Here we share the latest news and announcements of what is happening at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room. The stories shared here give you a peak into what is happening, who is visiting, and other interesting things we think you should know about.
fields.intro_tet: Iha ne'e ami fo sai notisia konaba saida deit mak akontese iha Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão

fields.intro_en: We love connecting with people. As a member, you receive the newsletter and are always up to date. Join our community to find out about what is going on at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room.
fields.intro_tet: Ami gosta tebes halo koneksaun ho ema hotu. Nudar membru, ita-boot bele simu notisia no sempre hetan informasaun aktualizadu. Mai hamutuk ho ami-nia komunidade atu buka hatene konaba saida mak dadauk ne'e akontese iha Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão.
fields.thank_you_text_en: Thank you for registering with us. We will get in contact with you shortly for you to come and get your membership card at the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room. Please bring a valid document such as Passport or National ID card.
fields.thank_you_text_tet: Obrigadu hodi rejistu ona ita-boot nia an ho ami. Ami sei komunika fali ita-boot iha tempu besik atu mai no simu ita-boot nia kartaun membru iha Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão. Favor lori dokumentu validu ruma make hanesan Passaporte ka kartaun Bilhete da Indetidade.

fields.intro_en: We love to connect with people. Inquire with us about any questions regarding the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room. We also love hosting diverse and inclusive events at the Reading Room. Let us know if you would like to book our space for an exhibition, training or any event that would make good use of our space.

Ami mos gosta atu sai uma-nain ba eventu oin-oin no inkluzivu iha Sala Leitura. Fo hatene ami kuandu imi hakarak aluga ami-nia espasu ba espozisaun, treinamentu ou eventu ruma ne'ebé mak halo ami-nia espasu sei fo folin wain ba ema barak.

fields.intro_en: The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room is above all a space for the community, we love to see your dream coming to life in our place. Whether it is a training, meeting, exhibition, book launch, film opening, discussion or anything else we will try our best to help you with facilitation. Please enquire using the form below and we will get back to you within 24 working hours.
fields.intro_tet: Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão nudar fatin diak tebes ba komunidade, ami kontente atu sai sasin ba ita-boot nia mehi sai realidade iha ami-nia fatin. Ami sei halo esforsu tomak atu ajuda ita-boot sira ho fasilitasaun tantu ba treinamentu, enkontru, espozisaun, lansa livru, loke filme, diskusaun ka eventu saida deit.

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room museum is proud to display a variety of permanent and semi-permanent exhibitions that inform visitors about Xanana Gusmão and Timor-Leste. Come visit us for free, today, to explore and learn.
fields.body_tet: Muzeu Sala Leitura Xanana Gusmão ho orgulho hatudu varius exibisaun permanente no semi permanente ne'ebe mak fo informasaun ba vizitante kona ba Xanana Gusmão no Timor Leste. Mai vizita ami ho gratuita, ohin, atu explora no aprende.

fields.body_en:
Gusmão was born in Manatuto, in what was then Portuguese Timor, to parents of mixed Portuguese-Timorese ancestry, both of whom were school teachers.[2] He attended a Jesuit high school just outside Dili. After leaving high-school for financial reasons at the age of fifteen, he held a variety of unskilled jobs, while continuing his education at night school. In 1965, at the age of 19, he met Emilia Batista, who was later to become his wife. His nickname, "Xanana", was taken from the name of the American rock and roll band Sha Na Na, who in turn were named after a lyric from a doo-wop song of 1957 by the Silhouettes.

In 1966, Gusmão obtained a position with the public service, which allowed him to continue his education. This was interrupted in 1968 when Gusmão was recruited by the Portuguese Army for national service. He served for three years, rising to the rank of corporal. During this time, he married Emilia Batista, with whom he had a son Eugenio, and a daughter Zenilda. He has since divorced Emilia, and in 2000, he married Australian Kirsty Sword, with whom he had three sons: Alexandre, Kay Olok and Daniel. In 1971, Gusmão completed his national service, his son was born, and he became involved with a nationalist organisation headed by José Ramos-Horta. For the next three years he was actively involved in peaceful protests directed at the colonial system.

It was in 1974 that a coup in Portugal resulted in the beginning of decolonisation for Portuguese Timor, and shortly afterwards the Governor Mário Lemos Pires announced plans to grant the colony independence. Plans were drawn up to hold general elections with a view to independence in 1978. During most of 1975 a bitter internal struggle occurred between two rival factions in Portuguese Timor. Gusmão became deeply involved with the FRETILIN faction, and as a result he was arrested and imprisoned by the rival faction the Timorese Democratic Union (UDT) in mid-1975. Taking advantage of the internal disorder, and with an eye to absorbing the colony, Indonesia immediately began a campaign of destabilisation, and frequent raids into Portuguese Timor were staged from Indonesian West Timor. By late 1975 the Fretilin faction had gained control of Portuguese Timor and Gusmão was released from prison. He was given the position of Press Secretary within the FRETILIN organisation. On 28 November 1975, Fretilin declared the independence of Portuguese Timor as "The Democratic Republic of East Timor", and Gusmão was responsible for filming the ceremony. Nine days later, Indonesia invaded East Timor. At the time Gusmão was visiting friends outside of Dili and he witnessed the invasion from the hills. For the next few days he searched for his family.

Come visit the Xanana Gusmão Reading Room to find out more.
Come experience the art of Inu Bere. His painting style is grand using broad strokes to visualize the outsize life and dreams of the big heroes of Timor-Leste that he seeks to portray.

Our Mission, Vision and Values

Our Vision: Create the reading generation in Timor-Leste.

Our Mission: To provide dynamic spaces for all people to access information and resources to improve their lives.

Our Values: Respect, Integrity, Quality, Community, Inclusivity. 

History of Xanana Gusmao Reading Room

The Xanana Gusmão Reading Room (XGRR) was established in June 2000 to serve as a safe place where children, youth, students, and the public at large, could access books and resources with a view to fostering a love of reading within the community. Since then, the XGRR has contributed significantly to library development in Timor-Leste and has hosted a range of educational and other activities aimed at nurturing pride in East Timorese culture and promoting skills development.

The Reading Room was established by Kirsty Sword Gusmão, the wife of Timor-Leste’s first post-independence President Xanana Gusmão. As founder and patron, Mrs Gusmão has been involved in its operation ever since it opened.
  
This complex houses loads of memorabilia from Xanana Gusmão, and there is a library, bookshop, exhibition space, audio visual area and internet available. Artwork on display includes those Xanana Gusmão painted while imprisoned in Jakarta.
